From: heiser@acs2.bu.edu (Bill Heiser)
Subject: Re: SLS considered harmful (wasRe: Bashing Peter MacDonald)
Date: 28 Aug 1993 15:38:08 GMT

In article <1993Aug27.202441.24476.chiark.ijackson@nyx.cs.du.edu> ijackson@nyx.cs.du.edu (Ian Jackson) writes:
>
>We have seen plenty of very elementary mistakes made with SLS, and
>then released on the unsuspecting world at large.  IMHO someone who
>makes that kind of mistake regularly is not enough of a Unix expert to
>administer a major system, let alone put together a release for other
>people.

Hey, even major corporations with hundreds or thousands of employees
working on a project make "elementary mistakes"!  When was the last time
you got a SunOS release with no seemingly-simple mistakes/bugs?  Not
too long ago, I got some software from DEC for SunOS, and it came on
a CD that was ONLY mountable on a DEC ULTRIX system!  How much more
of an *elementary mistake* can you make?

This having been said, I think some of the complaints we're seeing
re: LINUX SLS is the fact that many people are Paying for the product,
so it appears to be a commercial release.  I, for one, bought the
disk format of SLS.  Although being familiar with this kind of stuff,
I realized that this "cost" was just to cover handling, labor, and
disks, and that Linux itself is a free product, others, particularly
those new to freeware, might not look at it that way.

Those selling SLS for $99 or whatever should make it more clear
(and should be *required* to make it clear) that LINUX is not a
commercial product.



-- 
Bill Heiser    heiser@acs.bu.edu, heiser@world.std.com
               Boston University, Boston MA   

