From: jliddle@rs6000.cmp.ilstu.edu (Jean Liddle)
Subject: Re: SLS considered harmful (wasRe: Bashing Peter MacDonald)
Date: Sat, 28 Aug 1993 15:38:14 GMT

In article <1993Aug27.202441.24476.chiark.ijackson@nyx.cs.du.edu> ijackson@nyx.cs.du.edu (Ian Jackson) writes:
>
>I have to say that I think that all the criticisms of SLS that have
>been made recently have been perfectly reasonable and well-justified.
>Most of the support seems to be coming from (with all due respect)
>people new to the Unix community who are probably not always aware
>when things go wrong and what the problem is when they do.
>

I would agree that many of the criticisms are valid.  Those which have
been presented as constructive criticism and/or bug reports are quite
appropriate, and will probably lead to a better product.  However, some
of the posts did resemble "childish wining," which IMO is uncalled for,
and (to say the least) quite ungrateful to the long hours of hard work put
in by Peter, Linus, and many others.  This I find to be rather destructive,
as Peter et al have made significant contributions to the Linux community,
and were they to give up in disgust and stop contributing we would all be
the poorer for it.  The only people this would serve would be Bill Gates,
and possible AT&T/Novell.

>We have seen plenty of very elementary mistakes made with SLS, and
>then released on the unsuspecting world at large.  IMHO someone who
>makes that kind of mistake regularly is not enough of a Unix expert to
>administer a major system, let alone put together a release for other
>people.
>

Perhaps, perhaps not.  Much of the Linux community is learning UNIX
through Linux.  Althoug I have done much of my admin work on Sun's (indeed
I am now employed full-time doing that) I have learned a great deal about
the more subtle workings of UNIX through Linux, simply becouse it is not
as simple to install as SUNOS.  Not that I am opposed to easy installations :-),
I have been a user of MCC, SLS, and more recently slackware.

>I am grateful to Peter for being willing to put in the effort, but
>when all's said and done I have to say that IMO the Linux community
>might have been better off if he hadn't; perhaps the MCC release would
>have carried on across the gap, or someone else would have taken up
>the mantle.
>

I strongly disagree.  At the time that Peter first came out with the SLS
distribution MCC was alot more primitive, X was a nightmare to install,
and finding all the diverse unix utilities we now take for granted was
a full-time endaevor.  The SLS distribution, even in its buggy first
incarnation, was a tremendous boon to those of us who didn't have the time
to hunt down this stuff.  SLS has served many people (myself included)
very well over the months, and has provided an important evolutionary
step toward even better distributions (slackware, and possibly debian).
Even were SLS to vanish from the community now, its contribution would
go on being felt for quite some time.  Those who are comming out with
new distributions have Peter's experiences to benefit from, and can
avoid some of the pitfalls he has stumbled over from time to time.  This
benefits us all.

Currently I use the slackware distribution, but it is my hope that all of
the distributions which are now comming out will contribute to one another,
and that all of them will improve as a result.

happy linuxing, and many thanks to Linux, Peter, and everyone else for a
great system.

Jean.
-- 
Jean Liddle                                 
Computer Science, Illinois State University  
e-mail:  jliddle@ilstu.edu                  
