From: c@royle.org (Chris Royle)
Subject: Re: A nice linux story
Date: Sun, 29 Aug 1993 12:43:19 GMT

In comp.os.linux.misc, KarlKeyte wrote:
:> >However, whilst you are correct and your comment is justified, they feel that
:> >converters which do not convert directly to either assembler or machine code
:> >are less reliable than those that do.
:> >

:> ...but nearly all C++ compilers convert to C.  That's accepted, it's
:> pretty reliable and it's used very heavily in industry.  There's absolutely
:> no reason to mistrust multiple translation steps as long as one has faith
:> in each layer of translation.

:> Karl

Absolutely - I quite agree, but they have never met such a converter before,
and are really very skeptical (note they, not me) about a free operating system
for which they do not pay for support and don't really know how to use.

I think they'd be happier if they paid for the lot of it and could ring up and
shout at someone if it went wrong. Then they'd trust the f2c, even though it's
the same - it's the backup and promise of reliability that they're after, and
they don't accept that they are getting that with free software.

Don't get me wrong - I trust most of my linux setup to do it's job right,
and until proven otherwise would trust f2c (I've not tried it because I'm
not a fortran man myself). Unfortunately, I don't seem to be able to 
convince them to do the same.

Hmm.

Chris.
